 In this issue&hellip;
The editor reflected on 2 years of Special Reserve: memberships had shot passed 25,000, with 5,500 of those also subscribing to Official Secrets (and, therefore, Confidential). While there had been the usual summer lull in game sales, they were expecting a bumper Xmas due to the Amiga&rsquo;s popularity and had decided to also carry Atari Lynx, Sega Megadrive and CDTV titles.
The news included details of SSI&rsquo;s &ldquo;Secret of Silver Blades&rdquo;, a bunch of upcoming flight sims, Alexey Pajitnov&rsquo;s &ldquo;Tetris&rdquo; followup &ldquo;Welltris&rdquo;, along with rumours of a new adventure from Level 9 (&ldquo;Billy the Kid&rdquo;), a game based on the book &ldquo;Neuromancer&rdquo;, and Sierra bringing &ldquo;King&rsquo;s Quest IV&rdquo; and &ldquo;Colonel&rsquo;s Bequest&rdquo; to the Amiga. A hands on with &ldquo;Wonderland&rdquo;, the newest adventure from Magnetic Scrolls. An interview with FTL&rsquo;s president, Wayne Holder (they were behind &ldquo;Dungeon Master&rdquo;). The story of one man&rsquo;s quest to get the text adventure he created published. A visit to Mindcraft, who were behind &ldquo;The Magic Candle&rdquo;. A look at MUG (Multi User Game) &ldquo;Empyrion&rdquo;. Battlegrounds reviewed &ldquo;The Sword of the Samurai&rdquo; and &ldquo;Sword of Aragon&rdquo;. The final part of the round up of home-based adventure publishers/creators. An interview with Sierra&rsquo;s PR man, Kirk Green, including details of what people could expect from their new CD-ROM games. A crash course in typical adventuring puzzles for novices. Details of Play By Mail game &ldquo;Battlegrounds&rdquo;.

 In this month&rsquo;s issue&hellip;
The subject on the editor&rsquo;s mind was, perhaps unexpectedly for an adventure gaming mag, taxation as he had a good rant about how much money from each game the club sold went to the HMRC.
Games making the news this month included several horror games (&ldquo;Elvira&rdquo;, [&ldquo;Demon&rsquo;s Tomb - The Awakening&rdquo;][4403], [&ldquo;Mystery of the Mummy&rdquo;][4404]), the next title from The Bitmaps in the form of [&ldquo;Cadaver&rdquo;][4405], and some new games from Origin. Official Secrets had managed to snaffle a load of copies of Infocom&rsquo;s back catalogue which was a good excuse to take an indepth look at the legendary developer. A round up of recent war/strategy games. The second installment in a beginner&rsquo;s guide to adventure gaming. [&ldquo;Ultima VI&rdquo;][4406] was about to be released and there was a look back at the previous games in the series. In addition to that, an interview with Lord British. With doubts being cast on the continuing commercial viability of the adventure game market, there was a round up of active adventure focussed software houses. This month&rsquo;s featured Play By Mail was &ldquo;Arcania&rdquo; from Marlin Games. [4403]: [4404]: http://www.lemonamiga.com/games/details.php?id=1947 [4405]: http://www.lemonamiga.com/games/details.php?id=212 [4406]: http://www.lemonamiga.com/games/details.php?id=1250

postimage thimbleweed.png
The iPad has become my preferred platform for playing adventure games, so I&rsquo;ve been looking forward to this one. I backed the Kickstarter almost three years ago and it&rsquo;s been a treat to see it take shape - the dev blog posts and podcasts were worth it alone.
As luck would have it, my next overseas business trip is coming up in a few days which I hope will provide ample of opportunity to dive into it proper. It should at least help make those long haul flights go quicker&hellip;

 Since getting back into the C64/Amiga scene, one of the things I&rsquo;ve really loved is that there are still people out there making &amp; publishing games for the machines. So I finally got around to picking up a few. From Psytronkik there is:
&ldquo;Kung Fu Maniacs Trilogy&rdquo; &ldquo;Gravitrix&rdquo; &ldquo;X-Force&rdquo; &ldquo;Space Trip 2086&rdquo;. And one from Pond that I had been eagerly awaiting:
&ldquo;The Bear Essentials&rdquo; These should keep me busy for a little while&hellip;

 News #The console wars were heating up as rumours surfaced that Nintendo and Sega were working on 16bit machines. Neither the NES or Master System had managed to gain much of a foothold in the UK - both machines selling around 45,000 units each - but the tide did seem to be turning. Code Masters were rather bullish about the console market, with Operations Manager Bruce Everiss being particularly enthusiastic about the Konix Slipstream: &ldquo;I think Konix has the potential to be another Amstrad. He [boss Wyn Holloway] has wreaked miracles. I&rsquo;d expect the Slipstream to have an open road until 1990.&rdquo; Of course, the Konix never appeared.
The Atari 520STFM and &ldquo;Afterburner&rdquo; were tipped to be the big winners over the Christmas period. The only major chain selling Amigas and C64s was Dixons, while WH Smith had dropped the Spectrum and went all Atari.
Sir Clive Sinclair was back with a new product: a low cost satellite dish. Their main competition would come from Amstrad&hellip;
The high cost of rampant piracy was estimated to be around £7.5 million each year. In Denmark and Sweden, 65% of games were illegal copies.
Features #&ldquo;Commuting sucks&rdquo; said Mel Croucher in his piece on telecommuting, and I couldn&rsquo;t agree more. A lot of what he described has indeed come to pass (online banking and shopping), while others (home automation) are slowly becoming more common place. He finishes with the call to arms: &ldquo;Employees must recognise that there is an alternative to traditional ideas of going to work, and fight for their right to choose it.&rdquo;
TGM investigated the shady world of piracy.
At the recent PC Show, Domark&rsquo;s stand featured a Maggie Thatcher puppet from Spitting Image on loan from the TV show that was operated by computer. The technology behind the puppet and potential uses for artificial limbs were examined.
Notable Previews # &ldquo;Purple Saturn Day&rdquo; Ere Informatique - Amiga, ST, PC, C64, Amstrad &ldquo;Billiards Simulator&rdquo; Ere Informatique - Amiga, ST, PC, Mac &ldquo;Teenage Queen&rdquo; Ere Informatique - Amiga, ST, PC &ldquo;Temple of the Flying Saucers&rdquo; Ere Informatique - Amiga, ST, PC Notable Reviews # &ldquo;Chrono-Quest&rdquo; Psygnosis - Amiga, ST 86% &ldquo;Psygnosis are better known for their arcade adventures, their high game-standard has be retained for this, their first step toward the pure adventure world.&rdquo; &ldquo;Ultima IV&rdquo; Origin/Microprose - Amiga 86% &ldquo;However, playability matters most, and Ultima IV has hours of this.&rdquo; &ldquo;Powerdrome&rdquo; Electronic Arts - ST 93% &ldquo;Powerdrome is THE game for those of you with racing spirit.&rdquo; &ldquo;Kenseiden&rdquo; Mastertronic - 86% Sega Master System &ldquo;An immensely playable game together with quality graphics and presentation which pushes the Sega to new levels of entertainment.&rdquo; &ldquo;Rocket Ranger&rdquo; Cinemaware - Amiga 90% &ldquo;Excellent graphics, breathtaking sound effects and sampled speech. No one scene is particularly complex but Rocket Ranger is deep enough to ensure hours of play.&rdquo; &ldquo;Operation Wolf&rdquo; Ocean - Spectrum 87% C64 79% Amstrad 89% &ldquo;Undoubtedly Ocean&rsquo;s strongest arcade conversion title this Christmas, the Taito coin-op has had phenomenal success worldwide.&rdquo; &ldquo;Pac-Mania&rdquo; Grandslam - Amiga 92% &ldquo;With a minimum of pre-release hype, Grandslam have sprung one of the simplest yet most addictive games from the arcades. It&rsquo;s amazing what a third dimension and the ability to jump can do to revitalise one of the oldest game formats in computer history.&rdquo;

 News #Ariolasoft released a couple of screenshots from a new game which promised to be a &ldquo;totally interactive graphic adventure &lsquo;movie&rsquo;.&rdquo; The game, &ldquo;Wild West&rdquo;, received luke warm reviews, but it was notable in that it was one of those rarities at the time: a game developed behind the iron curtain.
Activision were to take on EA&rsquo;s excellent &ldquo;Racing Destruction Set&rdquo; with their own racing game with a built in editor called &ldquo;Fast Tracks&rdquo;.
Electric Dreams had snapped up the rights to Mel Croucher&rsquo;s brilliant &ldquo;Deus Ex Machina&rdquo; and were publishing a repackaged and repriced version for the C64.
British Telecom were having to appease customers of its new M.U.D. game after technical problems delayed the launch. The launch manager, Mike Anderiesz, said: &ldquo;There hasn&rsquo;t been a program of this size or complexity before. The problems we&rsquo;re experiencing are just last minute bugs.&rdquo;
Sandy White was back with a new game for the Spectrum featuring some very impressive 3D graphics. &ldquo;I, of the Mask&rdquo; was due out &ldquo;soon.&rdquo;
Commodore announced their C64 bundle for Christmas. Called the &ldquo;Commodore 64 Christmas Compendium pack&rdquo;, it would feature &ldquo;The Secret Diary of Adrian Mole&rdquo;, &ldquo;Music Maker&rdquo;, &ldquo;Designer&rsquo;s Pencil&rdquo; and a copy of the book &ldquo;The Growing Pains of Adrian Mole.&rdquo; The bundle would have an RRP of £199.
Irish software house New Concepts were touting their new surfing game for the Spectrum, [&ldquo;Surf Champ&rdquo;][764] as being the &ldquo;ultimate sports simulation&rdquo; and &ldquo;as near to the real thing as possible.&rdquo; The game came with a plastic surfboard which was act as a controller when placed above the keyboard. Reviews were mixed.
St Bride&rsquo;s had struck a distribution deal with Audiogenic for [&ldquo;The Secret of St Bride&rsquo;s&rdquo;][765] - previously the game had only been available via mail order. The piece described St Bride&rsquo;s as being &ldquo;the world&rsquo;s most unusual software house&rdquo; which was &ldquo;a school on the west coast of Ireland where grown women can pay to find out what school life was like 50 years ago.&rdquo;
Features #C&amp;VG got in touch with a host of bands (well, mainly their managers/promoters/PR people) to find out if there were any fans of home computers and games amongst the stars. Turns out there was - perhaps this whole computer thing might catch on. One tidbit: &ldquo;Martyn [from Heaven 17] is a former computer programmer and he even booked his holiday in Venice using the BBC.&rdquo;
The band Mainframe (Murray Munro and John Molloy) wrote a very light piece about the equipment they used.
Marshal M Rosenthal looked into online gaming (as in actual games, not how &ldquo;gaming&rdquo; is used these days to mean gambling) in the US, and the services that provided them.
British athlete Judy Simpson was dragged in to do a review of sports games. The winners seemed to be [&ldquo;Summer Games II][766] and [&ldquo;Winter Games&rdquo;][767].
The big Christmas holiday films were discussed. &ldquo;Legend&rdquo;, &ldquo;The Goonies&rdquo;, &ldquo;Cocoon&rdquo;, &ldquo;Mad Max 3&rdquo;, &ldquo;Lifeforce&rdquo;, &ldquo;Jewel of the Nile&rdquo;, &ldquo;Red Sonja&rdquo;, &ldquo;The Black Cauldron&rdquo;, &ldquo;The Boy Who Could Fly&rdquo;, &ldquo;The Emerald Forest&rdquo; were all about to hit the UK box office. Meanwhile, VHS owners could look forward to &ldquo;Time Walker&rdquo;, &ldquo;Brazil&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Last Starfighter.&rdquo;
Notable Previews #A huge preview for David Crane&rsquo;s latest: the excellent and terribly charming [&ldquo;Little Computer People&rdquo;][768]. This game utterly intrigued me at the time, and I&rsquo;ve always had the thought of doing an unofficial remake kicking around in the back of my mind.
Notable Reviews # [&ldquo;Tau Ceti&rdquo;][769] CRL - Spectrum 10/10 Game of the Month &ldquo;If you buy only one game a year - then get Tau Ceti. You won&rsquo;t be bored for another 12 months!&rdquo; [&ldquo;Wizadry&rdquo;][770] The Edge - C64 9/10 Blitz Game &ldquo;Wizadry is the closest thing we&rsquo;ve seen to a real-time animated Dungeons and Dragons style game - with many of the elements of he original role playing D&amp;D include.&rdquo; [&ldquo;Fairlight&rdquo;][771] The Edge - Spectrum 8/10 &ldquo;All-in-all, a great game. Certainly one for mapping freaks!&rdquo; &ldquo;Darts&rdquo; Blue Ribbon - BBC 9/10 &ldquo;Could keep you and your mates amused for hours.&rdquo; [&ldquo;Wizard&rdquo;][772] Ariolasoft - C64 10/10 &ldquo;Wizard is an extremely well programmed , well presented game - don&rsquo;t be put off by those who tell you it&rsquo;s just another platform game. It isn&rsquo;t - it&rsquo;s something else!&rdquo; [&ldquo;Impossible Mission&rdquo;][773] US Gold - Spectrum 10/10 Blitz Game &ldquo;Impossible Mission is a game any self respecting Spectrum owner should have in their collection.&rdquo; [&ldquo;Gyroscope&rdquo;][774] Melbourne House - Spectrum 7/10 Blitz Game &ldquo;It&rsquo;s worth getting hold of to stave off Marble Madness withdrawal symptoms while we wait for that game to be converted for home computers.&rdquo; [&ldquo;Hacker&rdquo;][775] Activision - C64 10/10 &ldquo;Hacker is an intriguing and complex game based on a new and refreshing idea. It&rsquo;s a winner.&rdquo; [&ldquo;Chimera&rdquo;][776] Firebird - C64, Spectrum, Atari, Amstrad 9/10 &ldquo;Overall, Chimera is an excellent game which raises the quality of budget games to a new standard.&rdquo; [&ldquo;Shadow of the Unicorn&rdquo;][777] Mikro-Gen - Spectrum 8/10 &ldquo;Is the Mikro-Plus a great new game innovation? We reckon that still remains to be seen with the arrival of the second game based on the TV cartoon series of &lsquo;Battle of the Planets&rsquo;.&rdquo; While [&ldquo;Battle of the Planets&rdquo;][778] was released, Mikro-Gen decided not to use the Mikro-Plus pack. [&ldquo;Fight Night&rdquo;][779] US Gold - C64 9/10 &ldquo;Barry McGuigan&rsquo;s World Championship Boxing maybe a more accurate boxing simulation - but if you want your boxing action to have a touch of humour then book a ringside seat for Fight Night.&rdquo; [&ldquo;Scarabaeus&rdquo;][780] Ariolasoft - C64 8/10 &ldquo;Scarabaeus is a challenge for the thoughtful gamer who likes a mixture of action and strategy. You need all your wits about you when there are monsters about.&rdquo; Charts # [&ldquo;Way of the Exploding Fist&rdquo;][781] Melbourne House - C64, Spectrum [&ldquo;Daley Thompson&rsquo;s Super Test&rdquo;][782] Ocean - Spectrum [&ldquo;Frank Bruno&rsquo;s Boxing&rdquo;][783] Elite - Spectrum, C64, Amstrad [764]: [765]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0006951 [766]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=2530 [767]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=2863 [768]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=1525 [769]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0005153 [770]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=2878 [771]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0001712 [772]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=3266 [773]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0002462 [774]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0002196 [775]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=1132 [776]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=469 [777]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0004424 [778]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0000458 [779]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=907 [780]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=2229 [781]: http://www.lemon64.com/games/details.php?ID=2824 [782]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0001222 [783]: http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0001848

 News #The Personal Computer World Show was about to happen and publishers were busy announcing/teasing their upcoming games. Full details of what was on display would be in next month&rsquo;s issue, but there was a boatload of previews to do.
Not one but two winners had been chosen for the Genesis competition Crash launched a few months earlier. The first was a shoot em up called &ldquo;Kat Trap&rdquo; by John Eggleton that would hopefully be out by Christmas, while the second - &ldquo;The Sewer&rdquo; by Martin Lee - was planned for Spring. While &ldquo;Kat Trap&rdquo; did make it out and was well received, &ldquo;The Sewer&rdquo; seems to have disappeared without a trace. Rather intriguingly, one of the two designs to receive an &ldquo;Award of Merit&rdquo;, one was called &ldquo;Leper Attack at Lemming Rock&rdquo; by Ian Bell - possibly the Ian Bell of &ldquo;Elite&rdquo; fame?
Features # Interview with Dave Perry. At 19 years old he had already become one of the star programmers of the UK games industry. At one point the question of when Dave expected to become a millionaire - around 30 seemed like a good age. Pete Tamlyn examined the state of role playing games (with particular regard to those on the Spectrum). He talked to various people, including Greg Follis (Gargoyle Games) and Mike Singleton. Rather interestingly, Gargoyle had designed the world of Graumerphy (&ldquo;Heavy on the Magick&rdquo;) before the actual game and had plans to publish a book about it - as far as I know, this sadly never happened. Charts #Top 30 # &ldquo;Quazatron&rdquo; Steve Turner/Hewson &ldquo;Batman&rdquo; Jon Ritman/Ocean &ldquo;Ghosts and Goblins&rdquo; Elite Adventure Top 30 # &ldquo;Heavy on the Magick&rdquo; Gargoyle Games &ldquo;Spellbound&rdquo; David Jones/Mastertronic &ldquo;Lord of the Rings&rdquo; Melbourne House Notable Previews # Gremlin had a busy few months ahead with &ldquo;Avenger&rdquo;, &ldquo;Footballer of the Year&rdquo;, &ldquo;Trailblazer&rdquo; and &ldquo;Future Knight&rdquo; all set for release. Electric Dreams had signed two movie licenses - &ldquo;Aliens&rdquo; and &ldquo;Big Trouble in Little China&rdquo;. While it had previously just focussed on the C64, Ariolasoft revealed it was going to show the Spectrum some love too. &ldquo;Deactivators&rdquo; would be first, followed by &ldquo;The Stole a Million&rdquo; and &ldquo;Camelot Warriors&rdquo;. Digital Integration announced its motorbike racing sim &ldquo;TT Racer&rdquo; which had taken Rod Swift two years to &ldquo;get the high standard he was aiming for.&rdquo; Martech had a bevy of games lined up: &ldquo;W.A.R.&rdquo;, &ldquo;Cosmic Shock Absorber&rdquo;, &ldquo;Catch 23&rdquo;, &ldquo;Uchi Mata&rdquo;, and &ldquo;S.D.I.&rdquo;. Steve Crow was finishing up &ldquo;Firelord&rdquo;, his first game for Hewson. Dominic Robinson had taken on what many people considered impossible: converting &ldquo;Uridium&rdquo; to the Spectrum (and doing a great job of it). Steve Marsden and David Cooke (of &ldquo;Techinician Ted&rdquo; fame) were working on &ldquo;City Slicker&rdquo;. Melbourne House were showing off &ldquo;Fist II&rdquo; and &ldquo;Dodgy Geezers&rdquo; (from the guys who wrote &ldquo;Hampstead&rdquo; and &ldquo;Terrormolinos&rdquo;). Pete Cooke&rsquo;s new game was revealed to be &ldquo;Academy&rdquo;, a follow up to &ldquo;Tau Ceti&rdquo;. This game blew me away with its depth - you could even completely customise the HUD. CRL announced that the much hyped &ldquo;Cyborg&rdquo; was coming to the Spectrum. Well, it never actually arrived and the C64 game itself was a complete disappointment. &ldquo;3D Game Maker&rdquo; looked interesting - it promised the ability to create Ultimate style isometric games. CRL had a couple of other games in production, namely &ldquo;Doctor What!&rdquo; and &ldquo;Room 10&rdquo;. I had the latter for the C64 and actually rather enjoyed it, though perhaps that was partly due to the fact that I had shelled out my hard earned cash for it. Elite had a two new arcade conversions in the pipeline. The first would be &ldquo;Paperboy&rdquo; followed by &ldquo;1942&rdquo;. Elite announced that it had rebooted &ldquo;Scooby Doo&rdquo;. It had been one of the most hyped games ever up until that point and the inhouse development had been abandoned as the gameplay &ldquo;didn&rsquo;t live up to the ambitious concept.&rdquo; Gargoyle Games were brought on board and managed to do a decent job (albeit a very different game than what was originally planned). Alligata announced &ldquo;Pub Games&rdquo; and &ldquo;Vandal&rdquo;. Macmillan had formed a new label, Piranha, and had an impressive line up of games on the way. Don Priestly&rsquo;s excellent &ldquo;The Trap Door&rdquo;, &ldquo;Rogue Trooper&rdquo;, &ldquo;Nosferatu&rdquo; and &ldquo;Strike Force Delta&rdquo; were revealed. Piranha had managed to grab the license for Terry Pratchett&rsquo;s &ldquo;The Colour of Magic&rdquo; and signed up the brilliant Delta4 to develop it. AdventureSoft were continuing to bring Ian Livingstone and Steve Jackson&rsquo;s adventure books to computer with &ldquo;Temple of Terror&rdquo; and &ldquo;Sword of the Samurai&rdquo;. A work by Isaac Asimov was being used as the basis for a futuristic adventure called &ldquo;Kayleth&rdquo;. Durrell were readying &ldquo;Chain Reaction&rdquo;, &ldquo;Killer DOS&rdquo; (which never saw the light of day), Clive Townsend&rsquo;s excellent &ldquo;Saboteur II&rdquo; and Mike Richardson&rsquo;s &ldquo;Thanatos&rdquo;. Rather interestingly, a remake of &ldquo;Thanatos&rdquo; is in production by Automata. Palace Software were busy working on &ldquo;The Sacred Armour of Antiriad&rdquo;. Argus Press Software announced a bunch of games from its various labels. &ldquo;Wibstars&rdquo; was a spoof game based on the software distribution industry where the player was put in charge of shipping &ldquo;product&rdquo;. Quicksilva had two games, &ldquo;Star Wars&rdquo; (based on the satellite defence program, not the movie - unclear if this actually came out), and &ldquo;Glider Rider&rdquo;. Mind Games had &ldquo;TimeTrax&rdquo;. Strategy specialists Lothlorien were finishing up two games: &ldquo;Johnny Reb II&rdquo; and &ldquo;Legions of Death&rdquo;. And finally, &ldquo;Miami Dice&rdquo; was a craps game from Bug-Byte. A follow up to the great &ldquo;Fairlight&rdquo; was on its way from The Edge. &ldquo;Fairlight II&rdquo; expanded on the original in pretty much every way and would include the ability to switch between two characters. Also due for release were &ldquo;Mindstone&rdquo;, &ldquo;Psi Chess&rdquo;, and an arcade conversion of &ldquo;Shao-Lin&rsquo;s Road&rdquo;. An adventure creator called &ldquo;Dreamscape&rdquo; was teased. It would be based on Bo Jangeborg&rsquo;s graphics utility &ldquo;Grax&rdquo; which he used for the Fairlight games. Sadly it doesn&rsquo;t look like this was ever released. Odin announced its next game would be &ldquo;I.C.U.P.S.&rdquo;, and would be published under its Thor sublabel. Firebird detailed several of its upcoming games. &ldquo;Hive&rdquo;, &ldquo;Future Games&rdquo; (oddly enough this ended up being released by Mastertronic),&ldquo;Empire&rdquo; and &ldquo;Druid&rdquo; were due to hit the shelves by Christmas. Mikro-Gen&rsquo;s next game would be &ldquo;SAS Strike Force&rdquo;. &ldquo;Frostbite&rdquo; was also mentioned as being the next game by Dave Perry, though it doesn&rsquo;t look like that was actually by him. Gargoyle Games had formed a new label, FTL (Faster Than Light), which would be publishing original arcade games (at the rate of 5 a year!). First up was &ldquo;Lightforce&rdquo; which showed of their new technique (called &ldquo;Lasermation&rdquo;) to hide the Spectrum&rsquo;s colour clash problems. Following that would be &ldquo;Shockway Rider&rdquo; and &ldquo;Samurai Dawn&rdquo; (which never saw a release). They also teased a new game called &ldquo;George&rdquo; which was &ldquo;an executive type game involving lots of artificial intelligence techniques, aimed primarily at data processing professionals.&rdquo; Notable Reviews # &ldquo;Dan Dare&rdquo; Virgin - 92% Crash Smash &ldquo;A game which lives up to the image of the cartoon character.&rdquo; &ldquo;Stainless Steel&rdquo; Dave Perry/Mikro-Gen - 89% &ldquo;A slick shoot&rsquo;em up without too much depth.&rdquo; &ldquo;Dynamite Dan II&rdquo; Mirrorsoft - 93% Crash Smash &ldquo;A very worthy successor to Dynamite Dan I!&rdquo; &ldquo;The Boggit&rdquo; Delta4/CRL - 90% Crash Smash &ldquo;This game is awarded a SMASH not just because it is amusing at the expense of a game and a theme familiar to everyone but due to its standing as an adventure - the game reads well, plays well, and the presentation is slick and polished to a tee.&rdquo; &ldquo;The Very Big Cave Adventure&rdquo; St Bride&rsquo;s School/CRL - 82% &ldquo;Certainly the Big Cave Adventure offers a great deal; it&rsquo;s not only a super spoof but a polished and well orchestrated adventure in its own right.&rdquo; &ldquo;The Graphic Adventure Creator&rdquo; Incentive - Crash Smash &ldquo;The response to this product should be extraordinary.&rdquo;

 News #Not a game as such, but the latest book from William Gibson, &ldquo;Mona Lisa Overdrive&rdquo;, was about to hit the shelves. To mark the occasion, the Cyberpunk theme would be visited several times in this issue.
What was billed &ldquo;the first mass-market desktop-publishing (DTP) packag&rdquo;&rsquo; was launched by mouse manufacturer AMS for PC-XT and AT compatibles. It featured a mouse, a handheld scanner and software - all for only £447.35&hellip;.
Commodore announced 600,000 Amigas sold worldwide (40,000 in Britain), which was considered &ldquo;satisfactory.&rdquo; Meanwhile, Nintendo had booked not only many of the stands at CES but also most of the hotel rooms where the show was to be held - a pretty good indication of who was &ldquo;winning.&rdquo;
Features # Mel Croucher took a look at the seedy underbelly of the increasingly popular Bulletin Board scene. Aside from a couple of heartwarming tales of people finding love, there were the concerns of the proliferation of obscene material, hate speech, weapon trading/making and people just being complete dicks. There had been calls to increase monitoring, but it was becoming more and more difficult as the number of people using the services grew. The more things change&hellip; The implications of the new CD-ROM technology were examined. It seemed unlikely that consoles or personal computers would be harnessing CD drives any time soon as they just didn&rsquo;t have the RAM to make it worthwhile. At that point even streaming video was out of the question due to the slow data rates and lack of grunt to handle decent compression. TGM spoke to Rare about the PC Engine, which was due for release in Britain. Rare had taken delivery of a unit in December and had had some people working on it. The overall impression was very good, but Chris Stamper pointed out that they were still committed to Nintendo (and indeed that commitment remained until Microsoft bought them). Marshal M Rosenthal visited the CN Tower in Toronto to check out the &ldquo;Tour of the Universe&rdquo; experience. The show made use of 70mm large format film at 60fps, hydraulics, and a sophisticated sound system to - apparently - impressive effect. The proliferation of new labels (i.e. existing publishers creating new labels for specific markets) was examined. The fact that it was still perfectly possible for entirely new publishers to be successful was mentioned, though it came with a warning: &ldquo;Unfortunately, as industries mature their veins grow taught and it becomes increasingly difficult for newcomers to break into the business. So, if you hanker after starting your own software label, now might well be the best time.&rdquo; The names of hardware and software companies, along with games were put under the microscope in a rather silly piece. One amusing bit: &ldquo;&lsquo;Top Ten Hits&rsquo; is probably the worst software house name around because it&rsquo;s so transparent, and &lsquo;Code Masters&rsquo; comes a close second.&rdquo; Mel Croucher gave a round up of his suggestions for which camcorder to buy. The rather new SciFi genre of Cyberpunk was outlined. References included the obvious &ldquo;Blade Runner&rdquo;, &ldquo;Neuromancer&rdquo; and &ldquo;Max Headroom&rdquo;, and also Walter Jon William&rsquo;s &ldquo;Hardwired&rdquo; and John Shirley&rsquo;s &ldquo;Eclipse&rdquo;. Notable Previews # Prism Leisure Corporation had two new games on the way &ldquo;Artificial Lives&rdquo; and &ldquo;Hot Shot&rdquo;. Prism also teased an upcoming game designed by Mike Suitin who had been a stage manager for shows like &ldquo;Hair&rdquo; and &ldquo;Jesus Christ Superstar&rdquo;, as well as the designer on many of Pink Floyd&rsquo;s psychedelic backdrops. It was originally designed as a stage show which never made it to theatre, but a 2 hour soundtrack had been recorded which was performed by Elaine Page and the cast of &ldquo;Hair&rdquo;. &ldquo;&lsquo;The Kristal&rsquo; will be a graphic and sonic masterpiece.&rdquo; I had never heard of this, but perhaps that&rsquo;s not surprising. The excellent &ldquo;Hawkeye&rdquo; from Thalamus (developed by Boys Without Brians). The third instalment of Melbourne House&rsquo;s &ldquo;Lord of the Rings&rdquo; adventures was revealed (though with no details and I&rsquo;m not sure it was ever released - unless they were referring to &ldquo;The War in Middle Earth&rdquo;. &ldquo;Barbarian II: The Dungeon of Drax&rdquo; from Palace was due in August. Domark&rsquo;s &ldquo;The Empire Strikes Back&rdquo;. Julian Gollop had formed a new company, Target Games, and their debut release was to be &ldquo;Laser Squad&rdquo;. Notable Reviews # &ldquo;Legend of the Sword&rdquo; Rainbird - ST 91% &ldquo;Legend of the Sword is most enjoyable to play, there are many locations - all with a graphical representation - and plenty to do.&rdquo; &ldquo;Interceptor&rdquo; Bob Dinnerman/EA - Amiga 92% &ldquo;Interceptor combines the realism of flight simulators with the fast action of Top Gun (the film) fighter combat extremely well.&rdquo; &ldquo;Earthlight&rdquo; Pete Cooke/Firebird - Spectrum 81% &ldquo;&hellip;Earth light is a compelling challenge, if not quite in the Tau Ceti class.&rdquo; &ldquo;The Great Giana Sisters&rdquo; Rainbow Arts - C64 82% Amiga 78% &ldquo;Addictive gameplay, however, turns this into one of the better German releases available in the UK.&rdquo; &ldquo;Gauntlet II&rdquo; US Gold - Atari ST 93% &ldquo;&hellip; US Gold&rsquo;s best product to date.&rdquo; &ldquo;Dark Side&rdquo; Incentive - Spectrum 48/128 &amp; ST 93% &ldquo;Dark Side, quite simply, is top class and certainly the truest arcade adventure yet seen.&rdquo;

 News #Huge news arrived just hours before this issue went to press - Amstrad had bought Sinclair for meagre £5 million. What would this mean for Sinclair products? The QL and microdrive would be likely casualties, but it sounded like Amstrad had promising plans for the Spectrum. Overall it was taken as a positive happening, though the alternative would&rsquo;ve been receivership for Sinclair. Sir Clive himself was to return to research. At the press conference where the sale was announced he said, &ldquo;Nothing ever goes the way I plan it.&rdquo;
The team at Crash were celebrating after the Audit Bureau of Circulations announced the latest circulation figures which showed Crash was the biggest selling computer magazine in the UK and Eire (89441 magazines sold).
Notable Reviews # &ldquo;Sam Fox Strip Poker&rdquo; Martech - 72% &ldquo;Mixed feelings, obviously, but Sam&rsquo;s endorsement seems to conceal a well presented poker game worthy the attention of card players.&rdquo; &ldquo;Max Headroom&rdquo; Binary Design/Quicksilva - 85% &ldquo;An original and entertaining arcade/adventure with plenty to do.&rdquo; &ldquo;Starstrike II&rdquo; Realtime - Crash Smash 96% &ldquo;A brilliant game.&rdquo; &ldquo;Attach of the Killer Tomatoes&rdquo; Fatman &amp; Dobbin &amp; S Ruecroft/Global - 89% &ldquo;A great game of a very bad movie.&rdquo; &ldquo;Cyberun&rdquo; ACG/Ultimate - Crash Smash 90% &ldquo;A good arcade adventure shoot em up!&rdquo; &ldquo;Ping Pong&rdquo; Imagine - 90% Crash Smash &ldquo;A highly playable and enjoyable sports simulation.&rdquo; The sound was by Martin Galway and received much praise: &ldquo;unbelievably good - Spectrum excellence&rdquo; &ldquo;Turbo Espirit&rdquo; Mike Richardson/Durell - 88% &ldquo;A driving game with a fair bit of gameplay behind it.&rdquo; &ldquo;The Way of the Tiger&rdquo; Chris Kerry, Shaun Hollingworth, Peter Harrap &amp; Marco Duroe/Gremlin Graphics - 93% Crash Smash &ldquo;An excellent development on the beat em up theme.&rdquo; &ldquo;Green Beret&rdquo; Jonathon Smith/Imagine - 88% &ldquo;Quite a tasty fighting game.&rdquo; &ldquo;Batman&rdquo; Jon Ritman &amp; Bernie Drummond/Ocean - 93% Crash Smash - &ldquo;A neatly finished game which does batman proud.&rdquo; Notable Previews # &ldquo;Graphic Adventure Creator&rdquo; Incentive Software &ldquo;Equinox&rdquo; Mikro-Gen &ldquo;Dark Sceptre&rdquo; Mike Singleton/Beyond - two versions were planned: a standalone game, and a play by mail version. The PBM would allow players to save their moves for each turn to a Microdrive cartridge and send them in to Mike Singleton who would play the part of the Shadow Lords. Mike would make his moves and send them back to the player. Charts #Top Games # &ldquo;Commando&rdquo; Elite &ldquo;Elite&rdquo; Firebird &ldquo;Back to Skool&rdquo; Microsphere Top Adventures # &ldquo;Lord of the Rings&rdquo; Melbourne House &ldquo;Marsport&rdquo; Gargoyle Games &ldquo;Dun Darach&rdquo; Gargoyle Games Interviews # Martech on their history and their development process. &ldquo;David Martin feels that the days when one programmer can produce an entire game from start to finish are over. &lsquo;Sure, there will still be room for a few Mike Oldfields in the software industry - people to design the game, implement the graphics, write the code and provide copy for the inlay. But people like Steve Crow (of Starquake fame) are very rare indeed.&rsquo;&rdquo; Stewart Green of Data Design Systems talked about his experiences with taking the plunge and setting up his own software company to sell his games. The company was run from his living room and he was struggling to find places to sell his games. &ldquo;Advertising sells games - a good game with no advertising gets nowhere at the distribution stage it seems, while a grotty game with lots of ad money behind it is likely to do well.&rdquo; Things looked bleak, but the company has continued to this day (well, their site hasn&rsquo;t been updated since 2009, but still). Features # A look at fanzines that had been sent in to Crash, all of which were produced by school kids. The full issue can be found here.
